<main class="page page-article">
  <header class="article-header">
    <p class="article-back"><%= link_to "&larr; Blog".html_safe, blog_path %></p>
    <p class="article-series-label"><%= @post[:series] %> &mdash; Part <%= @post[:part] %> of 6</p>
    <h1><%= @post[:title] %></h1>
    <div class="article-meta">
      <time><%= @post[:date].strftime("%B %-d, %Y") %></time>
      <span><%= @post[:reading_time] %></span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <article class="article-body">

    <p>Most deployment tools work by connecting to your servers and running commands. You execute a deploy from your laptop (or CI), the tool opens SSH connections to each server, pulls the image, stops the old container, starts the new one. Kamal, Capistrano, Fabric, and Ansible all follow this model. It's intuitive &mdash; you're telling your servers what to do.</p>

    <p>devopsellence works the other way around. <strong>Agents on your servers pull desired state and reconcile locally.</strong> The control plane publishes what should be running. Agents decide when and how to make it happen. No SSH. No push. No central executor.</p>

    <h2>How push-based deploy works</h2>

    <p>Take Kamal as a concrete example. When you run <code>kamal deploy</code>:</p>

    <ol>
      <li>Your local machine (or CI runner) reads the deploy configuration.</li>
      <li>It opens an SSH connection to each server in your fleet.</li>
      <li>Over SSH, it runs Docker commands: pull the image, stop the old container, start the new one, check health.</li>
      <li>It moves to the next server (or runs in parallel, depending on configuration).</li>
      <li>When all servers report success, the deploy is complete.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>This model is simple and fast for small fleets. One server? Deploys take seconds. Three servers? Still fast. The mental model is clear: you run a command, things happen.</p>

    <h2>Where push breaks down</h2>

    <p>Push-based deploy has structural properties that become problems as your infrastructure grows or your reliability requirements increase:</p>

    <p><strong>The deployer is a single point of failure.</strong> The machine running <code>kamal deploy</code> must stay connected for the entire deploy. If your laptop loses WiFi mid-deploy, or your CI runner times out, the deploy is partially applied. Some servers have the new version, some have the old. You need to re-run and hope the tool is idempotent enough to recover.</p>

    <p><strong>SSH keys on every server.</strong> Push-based tools need SSH access to every node in your fleet. That means distributing SSH keys (or certificates), managing <code>authorized_keys</code> files, and maintaining firewall rules that allow inbound SSH from your deploy machine. Every SSH key is a credential that can be exfiltrated.</p>

    <p><strong>Sequential bottleneck.</strong> Even with parallel SSH, the deployer must orchestrate the sequence: connect, pull, stop, start, health check, repeat. The deployer's bandwidth, connection limits, and error handling become bottlenecks. At 50 servers, you're managing 50 SSH sessions. At 200, it's a real problem.</p>

    <p><strong>No self-healing.</strong> If a container crashes at 3am, the push model can't help. There's no daemon watching your servers. You need a separate process (systemd, Docker restart policies, a monitoring tool) to detect drift and recover. The deploy tool only runs when you invoke it.</p>

    <p><strong>Deployer needs network access to every server.</strong> Your CI runner (or laptop) must be able to reach every server on port 22. This rules out servers behind NATs, private networks, or firewalls that don't allow inbound SSH. Home-lab servers, edge locations, and air-gapped environments are difficult or impossible.</p>

    <h2>How pull-based deploy works</h2>

    <p>In devopsellence, the deploy flow is fundamentally different:</p>

    <div class="article-diagram">
      <div class="article-diagram-chain">
        <div class="article-diagram-chain-step">
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-num">1</div>
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-content">
            <strong>Publish intent</strong>
            <p>You run <code>devopsellence deploy</code>. The CLI pushes your image and tells the control plane what should run (image digest, env vars, health check config). The control plane signs the desired state and publishes it to Cloud Storage. Your laptop's job is done.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="article-diagram-chain-step">
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-num">2</div>
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-content">
            <strong>Agents poll</strong>
            <p>On each server, the devopsellence agent polls Cloud Storage every 2 seconds. When it detects a new desired-state envelope (via sequence number), it downloads and cryptographically verifies it.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="article-diagram-chain-step">
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-num">3</div>
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-content">
            <strong>Local reconciliation</strong>
            <p>The agent compares desired state to actual state. It pulls the image, resolves secrets, creates the new container, waits for health checks, swaps Envoy routing, drains the old container. All locally, with no external coordination.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="article-diagram-chain-step">
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-num">4</div>
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-content">
            <strong>Report status</strong>
            <p>The agent reports reconciliation status to the control plane. The control plane aggregates status across all nodes and marks the deployment as complete when all nodes converge.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The key difference: <strong>the control plane publishes intent, agents execute independently.</strong> There is no central process orchestrating container operations across servers. Each agent is an autonomous reconciliation loop.</p>

    <h2>What the pull model gives you</h2>

    <p><strong>Deploys survive control plane outages.</strong> Once desired state is published to Cloud Storage, the control plane can go down. Agents fetch state from GCS, not from the control plane. A control plane restart mid-deploy doesn't affect rollout. Agents that haven't fetched the new state yet will pick it up when GCS is reachable &mdash; which is independent of the control plane.</p>

    <p><strong>No SSH keys on servers.</strong> Agents make outbound HTTPS connections to Cloud Storage, Artifact Registry, and the control plane API. No inbound ports need to be open (except for application traffic). No SSH keys to distribute, rotate, or audit. The attack surface on your servers is smaller.</p>

    <p><strong>No sequential bottleneck.</strong> All agents poll independently. Whether you have 1 server or 100, each agent fetches state and reconciles on its own schedule. The control plane doesn't need to manage connections or orchestrate rollout order. Deploy convergence time is bounded by the slowest agent, not by sequential SSH execution.</p>

    <p><strong>Self-healing by default.</strong> The reconciliation loop runs continuously. If a container crashes, the agent detects the drift on the next cycle (within 2 seconds) and recreates it. If someone manually stops a container, the agent brings it back. If the host reboots, the agent starts, loads cached state from disk, and reconciles. There's no separate monitoring tool &mdash; the deploy mechanism <em>is</em> the healing mechanism.</p>

    <p><strong>Works behind NATs and firewalls.</strong> Agents only make outbound connections. A home-lab server behind a residential NAT, or an edge server in a private network, can run the agent without any inbound connectivity. This is also why devopsellence's Cloudflare Tunnel ingress mode works &mdash; the agent establishes an outbound tunnel, and traffic flows in.</p>

    <h2>What you give up</h2>

    <p>The pull model has real trade-offs:</p>

    <p><strong>Deploy latency.</strong> With SSH push, the deploy starts immediately when you run the command. With polling, there's up to a 2-second delay before the agent detects the new state. In practice, most deploys converge within 2-4 seconds of publishing, but the latency is non-zero and non-deterministic.</p>

    <p><strong>State publication layer.</strong> You need somewhere to publish desired state. devopsellence uses Cloud Storage &mdash; a globally distributed, highly available object store. This is an additional dependency that push-based tools don't have. (Though it also provides caching and availability properties that push tools can't match.)</p>

    <p><strong>Harder to debug in real-time.</strong> With SSH, you can watch the deploy happen: see the pull, see the container start, see the health check. With pull-based deploy, the agent logs locally. devopsellence provides rollout visibility through commands like <code>devopsellence status</code>, but the feedback loop is indirect &mdash; you're reading status reports, not watching commands execute.</p>

    <h2>The deeper principle</h2>

    <p>Push-based deploy treats servers as remote terminals. You send commands and expect them to execute. Pull-based deploy treats servers as autonomous agents that converge toward declared intent. The difference matters most at the margins: when networks are unreliable, when the deploy machine goes down, when a container crashes at 3am, when you need to deploy to a server you can't SSH into.</p>

    <p>Kubernetes uses the same principle. The kubelet on each node is a reconciliation loop that pulls pod specs from the API server and converges locally. devopsellence applies the same architecture at a simpler scale &mdash; one app per server, no cluster coordination, no etcd, no scheduler. The reconciliation loop is the same idea, stripped to its minimum useful form.</p>

    <p>Next: <strong><%= link_to "Part 2 — The 2-second reconciliation loop", blog_post_path(slug: "engineering-decisions-part-2-reconciliation-loop") %></strong></p>

  </article>

